Spark Connect — the split-driver architecture.

In classic mode, your Python process is the driver. Pyspark talks to a java virtual machine in the very same process, through a bridge called py-four-jay. That java virtual machine holds the spark context and coordinates the executors. Your script and the Spark driver share a lifetime — if the script exits, the driver dies with it.

Spark Connect breaks that link. Now the Spark driver runs as a long-lived server. Your client becomes a thin library. It builds an unresolved logical plan, sends it over the network using gee-are-pee-see, and receives the results back as Arrow batches. The cluster keeps running in between client connections.

The cleanest way to picture it is jay-dee-bee-see. A database server is one process, your application is another, and the two speak a protocol over the wire. Spark Connect does exactly that for Spark.

And here is the key consequence. The client side has no java virtual machine at all. That is the whole point. Your client can be a tiny Python script, a Jupyter notebook, an integrated development environment, or a Go program — and none of them need to bundle Spark.
